<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The <strong>@HI{{ko}}-</strong> demonstratives generally relate to something near to the speaker, either physically or emotionally.
</p>

<p>
The <strong>@HI{{so}}-</strong> demonstratives generally relate to something near to the listener. They can be used to
refer to something that is not close to either the speaker or the listener if information about that
thing has already been provided.
</p>

<p>
The <strong>@HI{{a}}-</strong> demonstratives generally relate to something that is not near to either the speaker
or the listener.
</p>

<p>
The <strong>@HI{{do}}-</strong> demonstratives refer to something about which a question is being asked.
</p>

<p>
<a name="kore"><strong>@HI{{kore}}</strong></a>, <strong>@HI{{sore}}</strong> and <strong>@HI{{are}}</strong> are 
demonstratives and function as pronouns.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{<strong>kore</strong>wo kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please give me this one.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{<strong>sore</strong>ha}}@KJ{{resign}}@KJ{{write}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that a dictionary?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
<a name="dore"><strong>@HI{{dore}}</strong></a> is an interrogative used to ask the listener to choose one item from a
set of <em>three</em> or more things.
</p>


<p>
<a name="kono"><strong>@HI{{kono}}</strong></a>, <strong>@HI{{sono}}</strong> and <strong>@HI{{ano}}</strong> are
pre-noun adjectivals and serve to modify a noun. <strong>@HI{{dono}}</strong> is used with a following noun to ask "which" noun.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{<strong>kono</strong>}}@KJ{{book}}@HI{{ha}}@KJ{{private}}@HI{{nodesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This book is mine.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{<strong>ano</strong>}}@KJ{{direction}}@HI{{ha donata desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Who is that (person)?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{santosu}}@HI{{sanha <strong>dono</strong>}}@KJ{{person}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Which one is Mr. Santos?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ashitaga ichiban@KJ{{longing}}shii @KJ{{thing}}ha [dokodemo @KT{{doa}}]desu.
      <strong>kono</strong>@KT{{doa}}wo @KJ{{open}}keruto,dokodemo @KJ{{going}}kitai 
      @KJ{{place}}he @KJ{{going}}kemasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What I want most is a "magic door". When you open this door, you can go anywhere you want.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
<a name="donna"><strong>@HI{{donnna}}</strong></a> is used with a following noun to mean "what kind of". 
It can also be used to ask the listener to name one of a group which the following noun describes describes.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{nara}}@KJ{{good}}@HI{{ha <strong>donnna</strong>}}@KJ{{town}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What kind of town is Nara?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{<strong>donna</strong>@KT{{supotsu}} ga suki desu ka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @KT{{sakka-}} @HI{{ga suki desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: What sports do you like?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: I like football.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
<a name="koko"><strong>@HI{{koko}}</strong></a>, <strong>@HI{{soko}}</strong> and <stron>@HI{{asoko}}</strong> refer to a place.
</p>

<p>
<a name="kochira"><strong>@HI{{kochira}}</strong></a>, <stron>@HI{{sochira}}</strong> and <strong>@HI{{achira}}</strong> are demonstratives
that refer to a direction. They can also be used to refer to a place, in which case they are considered more
polite than <strong>@HI{{koko}}</strong>, <strong>@HI{{soko}}</strong> and <strong>@HI{{asoko}}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
<a name="doko"><strong>@HI{{doko}}</strong></a> means "where" and <strong>@HI{{dochira}}</strong> means "which direction".
<strong>@HI{{dochira}}</strong> can also mean "where", in which case it is more polite than
<strong>@HI{{doko}}</strong>. <br/>
<strong>@HI{{doko}}</strong> or <strong>@HI{{dochira}}</strong> are also used to ask the name of a country, school,
company or any place or organisation to which a person belongs. @HI{{nann}} cannot be
used for this purpose.
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<a name="ko-vs-so"></a>
In writing a word from the @HI{{ko}}-series may be used rather than one from the @HI{{so}}-series to
refer to something previously mentioned. In this case the author is describing something
as though it really existed then and there.
<p></p>

